
#)Checked Exceptions:
1)Checked exceptions occur at compile time.
2)Exceptions that the compiler forces you to handle using either try/catch or throws
Checked at compile time.
#)Must be handled using try-catch or declared with throws.	
IOException, SQLException, FileNotFoundException

Exmaple
import java.io.*;

class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        FileReader fr = new FileReader("xyz.txt"); // File may not exist
    }
}



#)Unchecked Exceptions (Runtime):
1)Unchecked exceptions occur at runtime.
2)Exceptions that the compiler does NOT force you to handle.
Compiler does not check them.

NullPointerException, ArithmeticException, ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException


class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int x = 10 / 0; // ArithmeticException
    }
}


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


#)How do you throw an exception from a method in Java?
You can throw an exception using the throw keyword.
If the exception is checked, you must also declare it using the throws keyword in the method signature.

Example â€“ Throwing a Checked Exception
Checked exceptions (like IOException, SQLException, etc.) must be declared with throws.
import java.io.IOException;

class ThrowExample {

    // this method may throw an exception â†’ so we use throws
    static void checkAge(int age) throws Exception {
        if (age < 18) {
            // manually throwing an exception
            throw new Exception("You must be 18 or above");
        }
        System.out.println("You are allowed to vote");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            checkAge(15); // calling the method
        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("Exception caught: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#)What happens when you throw a Checked Exception from a method?

Checked exceptions are exceptions that the compiler forces you to handle.
Examples: IOException, SQLException, FileNotFoundException.

If a method throws a checked exception, two things happen:
ðŸ”¹ 1. Method declaration must include throws
The method must declare the exception using the throws keyword.
This tells the caller that it needs to handle this exception.

void readFile() throws IOException {
    throw new IOException("File not found");
}


âœ… Here, throws IOException declares that this method might throw an IOException.

ðŸ”¹ 2. The caller must handle or declare it
The calling method has two options:
Handle it using try-catch
Declare it in its own throws clause

â€œWhen a checked exception is thrown from a method, the method must declare it with throws, and the caller must either handle it or declare it, otherwise the code will not compile.â€

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Example â€“ Handling Checked Exception
import java.io.IOException;

public class CheckedExample {
    static void readFile() throws IOException {
        throw new IOException("File not found"); // throwing checked exception
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            readFile(); // calling the method
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("Exception caught: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}

Output:

Exception caught: File not found


âœ… Explanation:

readFile() throws a checked exception.

main() handles it using try-catch.

Program continues running after handling the exception.


--------------------------------------------------------------------
Example â€“ Declaring Exception Without Catching
public class CheckedExample2 {
    static void readFile() throws IOException {
        throw new IOException("File not found");
    }

    static void callReadFile() throws IOException {
        readFile(); // propagate exception
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        callReadFile(); // exception not handled here, just declared
    }
}


Here, the exception is propagated up the call stack.

Compiler ensures that every checked exception is either caught or declared.



---------------------------------------------------------------------
#)Options to eliminate compilation errors
â€œTo eliminate compilation errors for checked exceptions,
 either handle them with a try-catch block or declare them in the method signature using throws.â€